  "text": "Berry, Krueger, and Simonet [CITATION_1] introduced algorithm MLS (Maximal Label Search) as a generalization of these algorithms. MLS takes as input a graph G and a labeling structure L and computes an ordering of the vertices of G, which is a peo of G if G is chordal. A condition in the definition of a labeling structure from [CITATION_2] ensures that MLS computes a peo of a chordal graph. A still more general labeling search algorithm called GLS (General Label Search) is defined in [CITATION_3] from a more general definition of a labeling structure, which captures classical categories of graph searches (general search, Breadth-First and Depth-First searches) in addition to the graph searches derived from MLS.",
